ce:section.ce:para:
Neglecting the Faradaic behaviour, it is necessary to analyze the electrocatalytic performance in terms of a materials double layer capacitance to compute ECSA. At various scan rates ranging from 1 to 200 mV/s, cyclic voltammetry studies were performed to calculate the ECSA shown in Fig. 13
                         (a, b). Using these data, the double layer capacitance was determined to be around 0.01 mF/cm2. As per equation No.4 in SI, ECSA = Cdl/Cs where Cs is the specific capacitance and the value of identical electrolyte is 0.040 mF/cm2 [64,65]. The calculated ECSA of n-CDs@Gd(OH)3 is 0.25 cm2 which enhances the faster kinetics by reducing the charge transfer resistance and surface resistance. From the fitted values, the Tafel slope can be computed with the charge transfer resistance. From Fig. 13(c), Log(1/RCT) vs potential values were fitted with the linear relation with a Tafel slope of 64.8 mV/dec which perfectly matches with the Tafel slope from the LSV curve (65 mV/dec). These results show that the EIS technique of fitting values reveals that it solely depends on the charge transfer kinetics of the electrocatalytic feature. The above results clearly states that n-CDs@Gd(OH)3 shows an enhanced catalytic property due to the correlation and synergistic effect of morphology, defects due to heteroatom doping and free flow electrons, combination of two different dimension. The performance of n-CDs@Gd (OH)3 in HER characteristics were compared with other works as per the table shown below (see Table 1
                        ).
